[1] UK (Yorkshire County, Leeds)
Date: Fri 12 Jan 2018, 5:29 PM
Source: LeedsLive [edited]
http://www.leeds-live.co.uk/news/leeds-news/almost-70-cases-measles-been-14149558


The number of measles cases reported in Leeds has risen dramatically - with an increase of over 60 cases in the last 6 weeks. There have been 69 cases of measles reported in the city in the past 6 weeks, compared to just 2 in the same period last year [2016/2017].

In the 6 weeks to [7 Jan 2018], covering [December 2017] and the festive period, 69 suspected cases of measles were reported to Public Health England (PHE) in Leeds.

While not all the cases will turn out to be measles, the number of reports is much higher than in the same period in the previous 2 years, the 6 weeks to Week 01 of PHE reports, when 2 cases each were reported in 2016/17 and 2015/16. Reports in 2016/17 were at their highest in the week to 3 Dec, with 31, falling to no reports in the week to 31 Dec, and 3 in the week to 7 Jan.

However, with PHE warning that recent outbreaks are linked to ongoing large outbreaks in Europe, with people who have recently travelled to Romania, Italy and Germany and who have not had 2 doses of the MMR vaccine particularly at risk, there is a possibility that the number of cases will rise again as people return to school and work following the festive break.

Across England and Wales, in the 6 weeks to 7 Jan, covering December and the festive period, 372 suspected cases of measles have been reported to Public Health England (PHE). Again, while not all the cases will turn out to be measles, the number of reports has risen when compared to the same period in the previous 2 years, the 6 weeks to Week 01 of PHE reports, when 142 cases were reported in 2016/17 and 115 in 2015/16.

The number of reported measles cases across England and Wales is at its highest level for this time of year since 547 cases were reported in 2012/13 - when there were major measles outbreak in England and Wales between [November 2012] and [July 2013], primarily concentrated in Wales but with high numbers of cases in the north of England.

Measles: Symptoms and the MMR vaccine
-------------------------------------
Symptoms of measles include high fever, runny nose, conjunctivitis and cough. A rash then usually develops, starting at the head and spreading to the trunk and limbs over 3 -- 4 days.

People are infectious from their 1st symptoms to 4 days after the rash appears. Symptoms start around 1--2 weeks after exposure to an infectious case.

Those who catch measles are generally very unwell and frequently admitted to hospital.

Complications from measles, including pneumonia, are common, and the death rate is approximately one in 5000 cases in the UK.

The MMR vaccine is available to adults and children who are not up to date with their 2 doses. Routinely the 1st dose of MMR is given between 12 and 13 months of age and the 2nd at 3 years and 4 months of age, before starting school.

Dr Mary Ramsay, Head of Immunisation at PHE, said: "This serves as an important reminder for parents to take up the offer of MMR vaccination for their children at 1 year of age and as a pre-school booster at 3 years and 4 months of age. Children and young adults who missed out on their MMR vaccine in the past or are unsure if they had 2 doses should contact their GP practice to catch-up. "We'd also encourage people to ensure they are up to date with their MMR vaccine before travelling to countries with ongoing measles outbreaks.

"The UK recently achieved WHO measles elimination status and so the overall risk of measles to the UK population is low, however due to ongoing measles outbreaks in Europe, we will continue to see cases in unimmunised individuals and limited onward spread can occur in communities with low MMR coverage and in age groups with very close mixing."

[Byline: Claire Miller]

