[4] New Jersey (Newark Liberty International airport)
Date: Fri 12 Jan 2018, 5:18 PM
Source: Argus Press [edited]
http://www.argus-press.com/news/state_news/article_97e42e26-a9ce-5c9c-86c7-493470c3e0c5.html


Health officials in New Jersey are warning passengers who traveled through Newark Liberty International Airport earlier this month [January 2018] that they may have been exposed to measles.

The New Jersey Department of Health says an international traveler with a confirmed case of the highly contagious disease arrived in Terminal C on [2 Jan 2018], departed for Indianapolis from a domestic terminal, and may have gone to other areas of the airport.

They say anyone at the airport between 6:30 AM and 5:30 PM on [2 Jan 2018] may have been exposed and could develop symptoms as late as [23 Jan 2018].

Anyone with symptoms of measles -- including rash, high fever, cough, runny nose and red, watery eyes -- should contact a health care provider before going to a medical office or emergency department.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to WHO, measles transmission had been considered interrupted in North, South, and Central America since 2002, when the last endemic case was reported in the Americas. However, as the disease has continued to circulate in other parts of the world, some countries in the Americas experience imported cases. The International Expert Committee reviewed evidence on measles elimination presented by all the countries of the Region between 2015 and August 2016 and decided that it met the established criteria for elimination. The process included 6 years of work with countries to document evidence of the elimination.

Even when a country is declared measles-free, indicating no endemic initiation of a measles transmission chain, virus transmission can occur following exposure during travel to locations where measles is endemic, or from an infected traveler entering the country. The index case also may become infected en route to a location, as in airports and on airplanes, as reported at 2 airports in the US in this ProMED post and the following one. For these reasons, it is important that even measles-free countries maintain a high level of immunization.

A Healthmap/ProMED of the United States can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5561190,106 and of New Jersey, United States: at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5561190,232 - Mod.LK]

